## Incomprehensible source code is ***dangerous***/***threatening*** to humans (but computers/AIs don't care)

### The Toyota "Unintended Acceleration" Case (2005–2010) – 89 deaths

This is perhaps the most famous modern example of "spaghetti code"
having lethal consequences. After a series of crashes involving Toyota
vehicles accelerating uncontrollably, NASA and software experts (Barr
Group) audited the source code for the Electronic Throttle Control
System (ETCS).

**The State of the Code:** Experts found over **10,000 global
variables** (data points that can be changed from anywhere in the
program). The code violated almost every standard for safety-critical
systems. It had a "Cyclomatic Complexity" score (a measure of how many
paths code can take) that was off the charts—literally un-testable.

**The Disaster:** Because the code was a "spaghetti" mess, it suffered
from stack overflows and memory corruption that would kill the
"failsafe" task. When the failsafe died, the engine would lock into a
wide-open throttle state.

**The Fallout:** Toyota recalled millions of vehicles and paid over
**\$1.2 billion** in a DOJ settlement.

