### Therac-25 Radiation Overdoses (1985-1987) – 3 deaths, 3 maimings

This is perhaps the most tragic example of "spaghetti code" and a lack
of fundamental understanding of source code. The Therac-25 radiation
therapy machine gave patients radiation doses hundreds of times greater
than normal due to concurrent programming errors (race conditions),
killing at least three people and seriously injuring three others.

**The Root Cause:** The Therac-25 was a radiation therapy machine.
Unlike its predecessors, it relied almost entirely on software for
safety interlocks rather than hardware.

**The Lack of Understanding:** The software was largely reused from
older models (Therac-6 and Therac-20). The developers didn't realize
that the older code had bugs that were previously "masked" by hardware
safety switches. When moved to a software-only environment, a subtle
"race condition" occurred.

**The Catastrophe:** If an operator typed commands too quickly, the
software would fail to set the machine's physical shield in place but
still fire a high-intensity beam. Several patients received lethal doses
of radiation because the programmers didn't understand the timing
nuances of their own inherited code.

