### Knight Capital Trading Disaster (2012) – \$440 Million in 45 Minutes

An old, dormant piece of code was accidentally reactivated during a
software deployment. The incomprehensible legacy code began executing
unintended trades at a massive scale, causing Knight Capital to lose
\$440 million in just 45 minutes and nearly bankrupting the company.

**The Root Cause:** The firm deployed new software to servers, but one
server was accidentally left running a dormant, decade-old piece of code
called "Power Peg."

**The Lack of Understanding:** The current engineering team didn't
realize this old code still existed or how it functioned. When the new
system triggered a specific flag, the "zombie" code woke up and began
buying millions of shares at high prices and selling them low.

**The Catastrophe:** Because no one understood how the old code
interacted with the new deployment, they couldn't stop it in time. They
eventually had to shut down the entire system to kill the process.

