### UK Post Office Horizon Scandal (2000-2020) – 736 False Convictions

The UK Post Office Horizon scandal is often cited as one of the most
widespread miscarriages of justice in British history. While the scandal
involved institutional cover-ups and legal failures, **source code
incomprehensibility** and systemic software bugs were the technical
engines of the disaster.

### The "Black Box" Fallacy in Court

The central legal issue was a presumption in English law that "computers
are reliable unless proven otherwise." Because the Horizon source code
was a proprietary, multimillion-line "black box" owned by Fujitsu,
sub-postmasters had no way to inspect it.

**Incomprehensibility as a Shield:** When postmasters reported "phantom
shortfalls" (money missing from accounts that they hadn't taken), the
Post Office and Fujitsu claimed the system was "robust."

**The Burden of Proof:** Because the code was too complex for a
layperson (or even a general IT expert) to audit without full access,
defendants could not prove the existence of bugs. They were essentially
told, "The computer says you stole money, and we can't see anything
wrong with the computer."

### Specific Technical Failures

When the source code was eventually audited during the 2019 High Court
case (*Bates v Post Office*), several critical flaws were found that had
been hidden by the system's complexity

The incomprehensibility of the code meant that even when Fujitsu
engineers found bugs (which they did as early as 1999), the complexity
of the legacy system made them hesitant to admit how deep the rot went.
It was easier to blame "human error" than to untangle a "spaghetti code"
mess that governed thousands of branches.

**Spaghetti Code** made it nearly impossible for independent experts to
find bugs quickly.

