### *A Fire Upon the Deep* by Vernor Vinge (Fiction) – entire star systems consumed by computer virus

This is the definitive "programmer archaeology" novel. Vinge (who was a
computer science professor) imagines a future where software is
thousands of years old.

**The Catastrophe:** An ancient, dormant super-intelligence (The Blight)
is "woken up" by researchers poking around in a 5-billion-year-old data
archive. Because the researchers don't understand the "spaghetti code"
of the archive, they accidentally unleash a virus that consumes entire
star systems.

**The Concept:** Software is rarely written from scratch; instead, it is
built on top of "legacy code" from thousands of years prior. Engineers
are called "Archaeoprogrammers" because their job is to dig through
layers of incomprehensible, ancient operating systems to find functions.

